INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '2afe6a54-d217-4acf-8d74-9bf1e0531ee7',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Groq + LangChain LCEL — Building Fast Chains with ChatGroq$escape$,
  $escape$Groq's inference speed makes streaming chains genuinely practical — latency is low enough that LCEL pipelines feel synchronous. Swap `ChatOpenAI` for `ChatGroq` and you get the full LangChain expression language with Llama 3.3 70B or Mixtral underneath.

The `ChatGroq` class from `langchain_groq` accepts `model_name`, `temperature`, and `streaming`. Pipe it into any `PromptTemplate` using `|` and call `.stream()` to get token-by-token output at Groq's 500+ tok/s throughput. Memory works identically — wrap the chain in `RunnableWithMessageHistory` and pass a `get_session_history` callable.

For tool-calling agents, use `create_tool_calling_agent` with `ChatGroq(model_name='llama-3.3-70b-versatile')` — Groq supports native function calling on this model. Bind tools via `.bind_tools([...])` before the agent node. Because Groq responses are so fast, multi-hop ReAct loops that would feel sluggish on other providers complete in under two seconds, making agentic workflows viable in user-facing products without streaming hacks.$escape$,
  $escape$from langchain_groq import ChatGroq
from langchain_core.prompts import ChatPromptTemplate
from langchain_core.output_parsers import StrOutputParser

llm = ChatGroq(model_name="llama-3.3-70b-versatile", temperature=0, streaming=True)

prompt = ChatPromptTemplate.from_messages([
    ("system", "You are a concise technical assistant."),
    ("human", "{question}")
])

chain = prompt | llm | StrOutputParser()

for chunk in chain.stream({"question": "What is LCEL?"}):
    print(chunk, end="", flush=True)$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
