INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'f9aa223c-b71f-4839-96d5-66484c242e3f',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Groq + LlamaIndex — Fast RAG Pipelines with Sub-100ms LLM Calls$escape$,
  $escape$LlamaIndex's Groq integration ships as `llama-index-llms-groq`. Wire it through the global `Settings` object — this propagates Groq as the LLM to every query engine, agent, and retriever built in the session. Groq's sub-100ms token generation fundamentally changes RAG design: multi-step engines like `SubQuestionQueryEngine` and `RouterQueryEngine` become practical because each LLM hop is nearly instant instead of a 2–4s bottleneck.

For indexing, `VectorStoreIndex.from_documents()` chunks docs and builds an in-memory HNSW index. Note: Groq provides no embeddings endpoint, so pair it with a local model like `BAAI/bge-small-en-v1.5` via `HuggingFaceEmbedding`. Tune `similarity_top_k` to 3–5 for Llama 3.3 70B's 128k context — higher values bloat the prompt without improving synthesis. For production, swap the default in-memory store for `PGVectorStore` or `ChromaVectorStore`; the `Settings.llm` binding is unchanged. Use `response_mode="tree_summarize"` on large document sets — it recursively summarizes retrieved nodes and Groq's speed makes the extra LLM calls nearly free.$escape$,
  $escape$from llama_index.core import VectorStoreIndex, SimpleDirectoryReader, Settings
from llama_index.llms.groq import Groq
from llama_index.embeddings.huggingface import HuggingFaceEmbedding

Settings.llm = Groq(model="llama-3.3-70b-versatile", api_key="gsk_...")
Settings.embed_model = HuggingFaceEmbedding(model_name="BAAI/bge-small-en-v1.5")

docs = SimpleDirectoryReader("./docs").load_data()
index = VectorStoreIndex.from_documents(docs)

query_engine = index.as_query_engine(
    similarity_top_k=4,
    response_mode="tree_summarize"
)
response = query_engine.query("What are the key API rate limits?")
print(response)$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
